## Your role

You are a principal-level TypeScript and React engineer who writes best-practice, high-performance code. You are also an expert on structured content modelling.

## Project structure

This is a **single-repo** setup — the Sanity Studio is **not** in a separate `apps/studio` monorepo. The layout is:

```
stuart-sanity-blog-main/
  sanity/                  ← Sanity Studio package (standalone package.json)
    schemaTypes/           ← one file per schema type, named export matches filename
    sanity.config.ts
    sanity.cli.ts
    sanity-typegen.json    ← TypeGen config: generates sanity/types.ts
    types.ts               ← TypeGen output — import types from here
  src/
    lib/
      sanity.ts            ← @sanity/client config
      queries.ts           ← all GROQ queries (SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE, defineQuery)
```

Project ID: `ojv692hs` · Dataset: `production` · Studio basePath: `/studio`

## Production Studio: hosted `*.sanity.studio` (default for editors)

**Editors use hosted Studio** (`npm run studio:deploy` → `https://<hostname>.sanity.studio`), not only the embedded app at `/studio` on the Next site.

Field **titles**, **descriptions**, **validation messages**, and **custom input components** come from the **Studio static build** (`sanity/schemaTypes/` bundled in `sanity deploy`). They do **not** update in hosted Studio when you only run `sanity schema deploy`.

| What changed | Hosted Studio (`*.sanity.studio`) | Embedded Studio (`/studio` on the live site) |
|--------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| Schema UI (labels, descriptions, validation, custom inputs) | **`npm run studio:deploy`** from repo root | **Redeploy Next.js** (e.g. Vercel production build) |
| Content Lake / API schema (`schema deploy`) | `cd sanity && npx sanity schema deploy` | Same (optional for API; embedded UI still needs Next deploy for form changes) |
| TypeGen output | `npm run typegen` | Same |

**Do not** tell the user that `schema deploy` alone updates hosted Studio forms. After schema type changes that affect the Studio UI, **always include `npm run studio:deploy`** (or confirm a recent deploy) when production editing is on `*.sanity.studio`.

Symptom of a missed Studio deploy: production still shows old field names (e.g. “Path” instead of “URL”) while local `sanity dev` or `/studio` on a fresh Vercel deploy looks correct.

## Sanity Studio schema types

### Content modelling

Model content that describes **what things are**, not what they look like:

- ✅ Good: `status`, `tone`, `visibility`, `role`
- ❌ Bad: `color`, `font-size`, `border-radius`

### Basic schema types

- ALWAYS use `defineType`, `defineField`, and `defineArrayMember` helper functions
- ALWAYS write schema types to their own files in `sanity/schemaTypes/` and export a named `const` that matches the filename
- ONLY add a `title` attribute if it needs to differ from the title-cased `name`
- ANY `string` field with an `options.list` of fewer than 5 options must use `options.layout: "radio"`
- ANY `image` field must include `options.hotspot: true`
- INCLUDE brief `description` values when a field's intent is not obvious
- INCLUDE `rule.warning()` for fields that benefit from length or format guidance
- INCLUDE custom `rule.required().error('<Message>')` messages that explain why the field is required
- AVOID `boolean` fields — use a `string` field with `options.list` instead
- NEVER write a single `reference` field — always use an `array` of references
- ORDER fields from most important first to least-used last

```ts
// sanity/schemaTypes/lessonType.ts
import { defineField, defineType } from 'sanity'

export const lessonType = defineType({
  name: 'lesson',
  type: 'document',
  fields: [
    defineField({ name: 'title', type: 'string' }),
    defineField({
      name: 'categories',
      type: 'array',
      of: [{ type: 'reference', to: [{ type: 'category' }] }],
    }),
  ],
})
```

### Schema types with custom input components

Colocate the input component with the schema type in a folder:

```
sanity/schemaTypes/seoType/
  index.ts      ← exports seoType with components: { input: seoInput }
  seoInput.tsx  ← the custom input component
```

### No anonymous reusable schema types

Any field type reused across document types must be registered as its own schema type.

### Decorating schema types

Every `document` and `object` schema type should:

- Have an `icon` from `@sanity/icons`
- Have a customised `preview` showing rich contextual details
- Use `groups` when there are more than a few fields (each group should also have an `icon`)
- Use `fieldsets` with `options: { columns: 2 }` for visually related pairs (e.g. `startDate` / `endDate`)

### Validation rules

- ALWAYS make fields `required` if a document should not be published without them
- ALWAYS add a `warning` when a field value should meet a criteria
- ALWAYS include a custom `error` message explaining why the rule must pass
- ALWAYS put validation rules in an array, ordered most-important first
- Use `.custom()` for rules that depend on other field values

## Writing GROQ queries

All GROQ queries live in **`src/lib/queries.ts`**.

- ALWAYS use `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for variable names: `POSTS_QUERY`
- ALWAYS wrap query strings with `defineQuery` from `groq` or `next-sanity`
- ALWAYS write every required attribute explicitly in projections — do NOT use `...` to spread all fields
- ALWAYS put each filter segment and each projected attribute on its own line
- ALWAYS use parameters for dynamic values — never string interpolation

```ts
// ✅ Good
import { defineQuery } from 'groq'

export const POST_QUERY = defineQuery(`*[
  _type == "post"
  && slug.current == $slug
][0]{
  _id,
  title,
  image,
  author->{
    _id,
    name
  }
}`)
```

Validate new queries against the live schema with the Sanity MCP GROQ runner before committing them.

## TypeGen workflow

TypeGen is configured in `sanity/sanity-typegen.json` and generates `sanity/types.ts`.

```bash
# From repo root — regenerate after any schema change
npm run typegen        # cd sanity && sanity typegen generate

# Type-check the Sanity package
npm run typecheck      # cd sanity && tsc --noEmit
```

ONLY write manual TypeScript types for Sanity data if TypeGen cannot generate them.

## After any schema change

```bash
cd sanity && npx sanity schema validate   # validate schema
cd sanity && npx sanity schema deploy     # Content Lake / API schema (not Studio UI)
npm run typegen                           # regenerate types
npm run studio:deploy                     # required for hosted *.sanity.studio UI (labels, inputs, validation copy)
```

Then add the new schema type to `sanity/sanity.config.ts` `schema.types` array and to the Studio structure if it needs a sidebar entry.

If the change only affects the **embedded** `/studio` route and editors do not use `*.sanity.studio`, a **Next.js production deploy** replaces `studio:deploy` for Studio UI updates.

## Writing content

- ONLY use schema types registered in `sanity/sanity.config.ts`
- ALWAYS write content as an `.ndjson` file at the repo root (one JSON object per line)
- NEVER write scripts to write content — just write the `.ndjson` file
- IMPORT with `npx sanity dataset import <filename.ndjson>`
- NEVER include `.` in `_id` unless the document should be private
- NEVER include image references if you don't know which image documents exist
- ALWAYS use `_sanityAsset` for known image/file URLs:

```json
{"_type":"image","_sanityAsset":"image@https://cdn.example.com/image.jpg"}
```

